groundspeak:long_description.#text:
The container is a lock n lock with camo tape placed where it can be easily seen when you get to the location. Be careful if you are allergic to poison ivy as there is some in the area.  

Years ago, (back in the teens and twenties), the area of Rt. 49 for the next couple of miles north went through a low area almost like a swamp.  I have been told that the locals and probably with some help from the state laid large logs side by side to keep the wagons and vehicles from getting stuck.  It was probably a pretty rough ride!

This cache is on private property with permission of the owner.  There is an entrance where you can pull in off the highway.  It's a little narrow, so be careful.  Please contact me if there is a problem  with the cache.

groundspeak:short_description.#text:
This Cache is out at lake view park located near two other great
caches. The view is beutiful and the terrain is not bad at all,
just a few hills which is why I gave the terrain a 3, although it
is a pretty good hike from the parking area to the cache. Getting

groundspeak:long_description.#text:
I have been Gabriel's Big Brother for a little over a year and it has been such a Blessing for both of us. One of the first things we did when I started hanging out with Gabriel was geocaching in fact, the very first Cache we ever found is less the 1500 feet from where we hid this one. We thought since this was the first Cache we had ever hid, it would be appropriate to hide it near the first Cache we ever found together. The cache is located at Lake View park which is kind of difficult to find if you have never been there. You might ask for directions at the Casey's gas station. The nice thing too is there are two caches located here as well and the place is beutiful. My Dad, used to take his Dog out there and play his guitar with his friends there back in the 1970's when he was in College.

Anyway this Cache will take you on a nice hike through the park, and you can actually keep the lake in sight all the way to the cache. It being our first Hide, we thought we would make it a good one. So this one won't be an easy one to find without the clue. I am not a fan of not finding the Cache so after the first to find, I will post a video clue, where Gabriel shows you where it is, because even after you know, it's still going to be fun to get too :] The container is actually a green paintball pod, if your a paintball player you will know what your looking for otherwise you might have to google it to find out what it looks like. Original contents are: A brand new in the plastic, with the tag on them, pair of Panama Jack Sunglasses for FTF, a rubber snake, poker chips, a gummy nose and ear, a red pen, a blue pen, a black pen and the logbook.

You can check out the video about Gabriel and I if you want since were new on the hiding geocaches scene :]. See our mentorship video here! Thanks and happy cacheing!

groundspeak:short_description.#text: This a quick park and grab with a full size ammo can full of goodies. The Cache is on private property, with permission of the owner, so please only seek it during daylight hours. The cache is in the woods, not in the memorial gardens, please stay out of the gardens and flowers. No worries about muggles here, accept for the cache owner who ma stop if they see you for a friendly chat.

groundspeak:long_description.#text:
Parking in the grass is clearly marked, but there are coordinates for that as well in case you need them. Please do not continue up the drive but use the appropriate parking to turn around and leave the way you came.

This Cache is being placed on Father's day weekend in memory of my Father, Craig Norman who passed on from this world on May 19th. His memorial was a beutiful testimony to the life he lived and even the lives he saved. Craig graduated from Glenbard West High School 1970. He later graduated from Eastern Illinois University B.S. degree, and St. Louis University School of Nursing B.S.N degree Magna cum Laude. In 1993, he graduated from Bradley University with a M.S. degree in Anesthesia. He worked as a Nurse Anesthetist at several locations, most recently in Palm Bay, FL. Craig especially enjoyed spending time with his sons skiing, playing golf, paintball and of course geocaching. He was a talented musician and enjoyed sharing his gift of music with family and others. You can listen to audio of the memorial service at this Link.

In the memorial garden's by the Cache you will see a smoke tree which is a symbol of my Father's beutiful life as well as a rock that signifies the importance of the Norman family to him. I still remember the first time I took my Dad geocaching he was floored that people would take so much time to setup the Cache and by how creative people were in hiding as well by how much fun it was to try and find them. I think he would be thrilled that a Cache is setup in his, and that you are taking the time to find it. Happy Hunting!

N 39° 30.476 W 088° 07.065
You can park in the mowed grass, parking is clearly marked by a geocache parking sign and you can back out into the driveway.

groundspeak:short_description.#text: There have been many battles that have taken place in the woods surrounding this cache. It all began with my Dad and Brother, and our very first Brass Eagle Talon paintball guns. Many have made fond memories here. Even during a time when my Dad was in a wheel chair, he would still wheel himself out and play. This cache is a celebration of all the battles and fun many have had here. The cache attempts to put you in the place of many who have come before you engaging in the games.

groundspeak:long_description.#text:
This cache is on private property and is maintained by the property owners. You can take the parts of the cache with you, if you would like as you advance on your mission, just make sure you return them to where you found them in order to avoid hindering the progress of future cachers. At the first way point you will need to search a 10 foot radius. Your mission if you choose to accept it, is to find the ammunition stash, equip for battle and defend the final position, to claim victory. This cache begins with an uphill battle in which you will have to use stealth to traverse difficult terrain undetected, to the ammunition and equipment stash. After you are fully equipped make your way to the final battle front to claim your victory.

One thing I really enjoyed while I (Mrs. S) was at Eastern were the flower beds in so many spots along the walkways.  No matter what time of year it was, there was always something to see when traveling from class to class.  I enjoyed all the labeled trees, too, and it's nice to see that new students and visitors to campus can still learn which tree is which.  In fact, there is now a plaque in the ground dedicated to the gingko trees just north of the garden highlighted in this cache.  (Thank goodness, our visit was in the spring and NOT when these trees put forth their smelly fruit!)

As for the cache, we checked out a place or two where we thought the container might be, but when we found it, we saw that there was no place to record our initials, although we squeezed them on.  And we wondered why the recent logs hadn't mentioned anything about the shortage of space... and we wondered why a lot of the dates we saw on that filled log sheet were from 2014.

As I was putting the cache back where we had found it, trying to get it securely out of sight, my fingers touched something that turned out to be a second identical container.  This one appeared to be a newer one, so we initialed that log, too, and then placed both containers together.  Perhaps the CO would like to pick one of them up to use as a future spare or to place another cache somewhere.

So that was our adventure at Flowerdoc's garden.  We enjoyed our time in the area today, and we are most certainly glad that there is no passing date on that commemorative stone!  [;)]  Thanks for the hide at "your" garden, Flowerdoc!

Chess is a game of strategy, intuition, and creativity. While you may not need all of those traits to find this cache, they'll certainly help! The cache is located at N 39° 28.ABC W 088° 10.DEF

A – Number of rows/columns on a standard board
B – Amount of pawns a player begins a game with
C – Minimum number of moves for Nb1 --> Ng5
D – Minimum number of moves for Kd1 --> Ke5
E – Maximum amount of spaces a pawn can move + Minimum number of moves for Bc8 --> Ba4 + Amount of queens a player begins with
F – Amount of spaces moved for Bf1 --> Bc4 - Minimum number of moves for Rc7 --> Re2

groundspeak:short_description.#text:
This is a gadget cache in the woods.  Get ready to sit a spell and work through the puzzels to get to the log book.  The logbook is protected by a GeoVersion of Ransomware. See the description for more details!

UPDATE!

Sounds like we had a little "Mini-Moga" with three or four cachers at GZ all trying to make heads or tails out of the puzzle. CONGRATS TO RANDO60 ON BEING THE FIRST CODE BREAKER!

groundspeak:long_description.#text:
CryptoLocker is / was a ransomware computer trojan which targeted computers running Microsoft Windows. When activated, the malware encrypted certain types of files stored on local and mounted network drives using RSA public-key cryptography, with the private key stored only on the malware's control servers. The malware then displayed a message which offered to decrypt the data if a payment was made by a stated deadline, and threatened to delete the private key if the deadline passed. At the time of this writing a similar ransomeware is hitting US & Canadian hospital. (http://goo.gl/GCa2UP)

THIS GEOCACHE IS HOLDING YOUR LOG ENTRY RANSOM

UNTIL YOU CAN PROVIDE THE CORRECT UNIQUE CODE!

There are a few “crypto tools” that are supplied for you to get to the final goal - the log book with your personal encryption code.  Please ONLY use our tools - do not damage any containers or tools while working on the cache.  On the log sheet each log entry has a unique hexadecimal code.  When you sign the log COPY DOWN THE UNIQUE CODE for the log entry you signed.  When you log the find on geocaching.com INCLUDE THE UNIQUE CODE FOR YOUR SIGNATURE AS PART OF YOUR ONLINE LOG ENTRY.

There are FOUR containers that need to be accessed to reach the log.  The FIRST container is NOT locked and gets you to the other containers. DO NOT ALTER, REMOVE OR CHANGE ANY OF THE CRYPTO TOOLS. Also please do not log any clues or solutions to the puzzles in the cache - let the next cacher cuss it as much as you did!

ENJOY!

 

Additional Waypoints

groundspeak:short_description.#text:
Relax and enjoy the native Illinois scenery at Douglas-Hart Nature Center! A short hike (or longer, if you take the scenic route...) with so many rewards. Enjoy the newest Douglas-Hart feature! (And help us take good care of it). 

Trail is flat and easy to walk. Wheelchairs and strollers can get very near to this destination by using the limestone trails.

Don't forget your binoculars, camera, and/or stale bread to feed the critters.

groundspeak:long_description.#text:
The Douglas-Hart Nature Center is located at 2204 DeWitt Avenue East, the corner of Lerna Road and DeWitt Avenue. The Douglas-Hart Nature Center consists of over 70 acres of native Illinois habitat including prairie, woodland, and wetland.
 

The property includes a visitor center with several amenities including restrooms. The nature center is open Monday - Friday 8am-4pm, Saturday 10am-4pm, and Sundays from 1-4pm. Trails are open daily, sunrise to sunset.

The Douglas-Hart Nature Center is is owned and maintained by the Douglas-Hart Foundation. The foundation was created in 1963 by owner, Helen Douglas-Hart who had a dream of returned farmland to its natural setting prior to human settlement. The center boasts a core team of diverse staff members and his governed by members of the community who make up the Board of Directors. As a non-profit organization, the Douglas-Hart Nature Center receives no tax support.

Site Rules:

  • Dogs must be leashed and cleaned up after.
  • Fishing is not permitted.
  • This cache is owned & maintained by the Douglas-Hart Nature Center staff.
